<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06208202 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06208202 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  A scandal involving covert government funding of political groups broadenedtoday with a report that police in South Africa helped set up and run a blacktrade union to counter anti-government labor groups.;    The JohannesburgWeekly Mail said it had obtained secret official documents showing police andthe conservative Inkatha Freedom Party set up and ran the United Workers Unionof South Africa as a joint project.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  S. AFRICAN POLICE CITED IN FUND SCANDAL  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign News in brief  </MEMO><TEXT>     Inkatha's leaders have been denying they had any formal ties with theunion. Opponents have charged that the union uses violence to try to counterthe larger Congress of South African Trade Unions, which supports the AfricanNational Congress, a bitter rival of Inkatha.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  From Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910726  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  116  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday July 26, 199100208202,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>